have undermined the separation of powers system in the last five decades, across a diverse array of partisan and policy landscapes.As each chapter demonstrates, member lawsuits are an outlet for frustrated members of both parties who cannot get their House and Senate colleagues to confront overweening presidential action through normal legislative processes. But these lawsuits often backfire - leaving Congress as an institution even more disadvantaged. Jasmine Farrier argues these suits are more symptoms of constitutional dysfunction than the cure. Constitutional Dysfunction on Trial shows federal judges will not and cannot restore the separation of powers system alone. Fifty years of congressional atrophy cannot be reversed in court.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 30. Aug 2021) 0aExecutive powerzUnited StatesvCases. 0aExecutive powerzUnited StatesxCases. 0aExecutive-legislative relationszUnited States. 0aJudicial powerzUnited StatesvCases. 0aJudicial powerzUnited StatesxCases. 0aLegislative powerzUnited StatesvCases. 0aLegislative powerzUnited StatesxCases. 0aPolitical questions and judicial powerzUnited States. 0aSeparation of powerszUnited StatesvCases. 0aSeparation of powerszUnited StatesxCases. 4aLegal History & Studies. 4aPolitical Science & Political History. 4aU.S. History. 7aLAW / Constitutional.2bisacsh  aconstitution, congress, president, court, war powers.08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertCornell University Press Complete eBook-Package 2019z978311065198008iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019 Englishz978311061076508iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE COMPLETE 2019z9783110664232oZDB-23-DGG08iTitle is part of eBook package:dDe GruytertEBOOK PACKAGE Economics, Law & Social Sciences 2019 ENGz9